<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ceanothus cordulatus </i>is a spreading, many-stemmed, thorny shrub that grows to 1.5 m tall. Its roots harbor nitrogen-fixing actinomycetes (Oakley et al. 2003). Shrubs produce abundant seed that is propelled a short distance when capsules open. Seeds may be consumed by ants, birds, and rodents, but many accumulate in the duff and soil as a seed bank (Fross and Wilken 2006, Reeves 2006a). <br/>
<br/>
Distinct patches of <i>C. cordulatus </i>are common in montane zones, particularly in the Sierra Nevada and southern Cascades. They develop in disturbed forest openings, including after fires and clear-cuts. Stands are transitional to various kinds of montane and subalpine forests (Dyer and O’Beck 2005). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
