<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Ceanothus cordulatus </i>stands regenerate rapidly from the seed bank and from sprouting after fire, especially after low- to moderate-intensity fires. Dense stands develop within 5 years. Cold and heat stratification is needed for germination, and seeds germinate after fire or other disturbance. Shrubs vigorously sprout from the root crown if branches are top-killed or cut (Dyer and O’Beck 2005, Reeves 2006a). Individual plants tend not to live more than 2-4 decades, and they often die or senesce with shading by over-topping young conifers. However, <i>C. cordulatus </i>can occur in later successional stages, including in sites in the central Sierra Nevada and the San Bernardino Mountains (Reeves 2006a).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
