    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ac-e, Ag-u). Extensive stands are uncommon in the section. The species is more commonly seen as individuals, as clumps in forest openings, or as a secondary component of other shrubland types.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dd, Dk). Stands occur in the Glass Mountain area just east of the Sierra crest and in the Sweetwater Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba). Stands occupy recent clear-cuts and burned areas in <i>Abies concolor-Pinus lambertiana</i> forests in the Yolla Bolly Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea-r, Et-u). Described stands come from the western slope at Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b) and at Teakettle Experimental Forest (North et al. 2002).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Be, Bh, Bm). Small stands occur in the San Bernardino, San Gabriel, and San Jacinto mountains. Minnich (1999) found <i>Ceanothus cordulatus</i> establishing in the San Bernardino Mountains without fire from seed caches.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Da, Dd, Df-g, Di-m). Stands occur in disturbed areas in montane conifer forests throughout the section.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ceanothus cordulatus </i>is killed by high-intensity fire, and seed banks can be depleted by frequent fires. Stands dominated by <i>C. cordulatus </i>usually indicate the area was burned or clear-cut recently. As a dominant shrub in forest openings or as a forest understory plant, <i>C. cordulatus </i>is an important resource for available nitrogen in these forests (Oakley et al. 2003). Site quality is important in determining the growth rate of the shrubs and conifers, which replace the shrubs in time. </div>
</div>

    

    

